    "John Trapp": "He is able to succour ] And no less apt than able; as he that hath been poor, or troubled with toothache, will pity those that are so. Queen Elizabeth said in her speech to the children of Christ\u2019s hospital, as she rode through Fleet Street, We are orphans all; let me enjoy your prayers, and ye shall be sure of mine assistance. Non ignara mali, miseris succurrere disco.\n18. The angels (say Proculus the Platonist and Plutarch) are messengers that carry God\u2019s mind to men and men\u2019s requests to God. {a} But who told them all this? Egregie dicis, sed quomodo probas? said Aristotle of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`, may we better say of these bold affirmers. {a} \u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b8\u03bc\u03b5\u03c5\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0398\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b1\u03bd\u03b8\u03bf\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2.\nVer.\n18. He is able to succour] And no less apt than able; as he that hath been poor, or troubled with toothache, will pity those that are so. Queen Elizabeth said in her speech to the children of Christ\u2019s hospital, as she rode through Fleet Street, We are orphans all; let me enjoy your prayers, and ye shall be sure of mine assistance. Non ignara mali, miseris succurrere disco.\n18. For ye are not come, &c.] q.d. You are not under the law, but under grace, beware therefore of profaneness and licentiousness. For think you that God hath hired you to be wicked? [v_Jer_7_10] are you delivered to do all these abominations #Jer 7:"
